42Lk 17:11 Now on his way to Jerusalem, Jesus traveled along the border between Samaria and Galilee.
42Lk 17:12 As he was going into a village, ten men who had leprosy met him. They stood at a distance
42Lk 17:13 and called out in a loud voice, "Jesus, Master, have pity on us!"
42Lk 17:14 When he saw them, he said, "Go, show yourselves to the priests." And as they went, they were cleansed.
42Lk 17:15 One of them, when he saw he was healed, came back, praising God in a loud voice.
42Lk 17:16 He threw himself at Jesus' feet and thanked him--and he was a Samaritan.
42Lk 17:17 Jesus asked, "Were not all ten cleansed? Where are the other nine?
42Lk 17:18 Was no one found to return and give praise to God except this foreigner?"
42Lk 17:19 Then he said to him, "Rise and go; your faith has made you well."
42Lk 17:20 Once, having been asked by the Pharisees when the kingdom of God would come, Jesus replied, "The kingdom of God does not come with your careful observation,
42Lk 17:21 nor will people say, 'Here it is,' or 'There it is,' because the kingdom of God is within you."
42Lk 17:22 Then he said to his disciples, "The time is coming when you will long to see one of the days of the Son of Man, but you will not see it.
42Lk 17:23 Men will tell you, 'There he is!' or 'Here he is!' Do not go running off after them.
42Lk 17:24 For the Son of Man in his day will be like the lightning, which flashes and lights up the sky from one end to the other.
42Lk 17:25 But first he must suffer many things and be rejected by this generation.
42Lk 17:26 "Just as it was in the days of Noah, so also will it be in the days of the Son of Man.
42Lk 17:27 People were eating, drinking, marrying and being given in marriage up to the day Noah entered the ark. Then the flood came and destroyed them all.
42Lk 17:28 "It was the same in the days of Lot. People were eating and drinking, buying and selling, planting and building.
42Lk 17:29 But the day Lot left Sodom, fire and sulfur rained down from heaven and destroyed them all.
42Lk 17:30 "It will be just like this on the day the Son of Man is revealed.
42Lk 17:31 On that day no one who is on the roof of his house, with his goods inside, should go down to get them. Likewise, no one in the field should go back for anything.
42Lk 17:32 Remember Lot's wife!
42Lk 17:33 Whoever tries to keep his life will lose it, and whoever loses his life will preserve it.
42Lk 17:34 I tell you, on that night two people will be in one bed; one will be taken and the other left.
42Lk 17:35 Two women will be grinding grain together; one will be taken and the other left."
42Lk 17:36 Two men will be in the field; one will be taken and the other left.
42Lk 17:37 "Where, Lord?" they asked. He replied, "Where there is a dead body, there the vultures will gather."
42Lk 18:1 Then Jesus told his disciples a parable to show them that they should always pray and not give up.
42Lk 18:2 He said£º "In a certain town there was a judge who neither feared God nor cared about men.
42Lk 18:3 And there was a widow in that town who kept coming to him with the plea, 'Grant me justice against my adversary.'
42Lk 18:4 "For some time he refused. But finally he said to himself, 'Even though I don't fear God or care about men,
42Lk 18:5 yet because this widow keeps bothering me, I will see that she gets justice, so that she won't eventually wear me out with her coming!'"
42Lk 18:6 And the Lord said, "Listen to what the unjust judge says.
42Lk 18:7 And will not God bring about justice for his chosen ones, who cry out to him day and night? Will he keep putting them off?
42Lk 18:8 I tell you, he will see that they get justice, and quickly. However, when the Son of Man comes, will he find faith on the earth?"
42Lk 18:9 To some who were confident of their own righteousness and looked down on everybody else, Jesus told this parable£º
42Lk 18:10 "Two men went up to the temple to pray, one a Pharisee and the other a tax collector.
42Lk 18:11 The Pharisee stood up and prayed about himself£º 'God, I thank you that I am not like other men--robbers, evildoers, adulterers--or even like this tax collector.
42Lk 18:12 I fast twice a week and give a tenth of all I get.'
42Lk 18:13 "But the tax collector stood at a distance. He would not even look up to heaven, but beat his breast and said, 'God, have mercy on me, a sinner.'
42Lk 18:14 "I tell you that this man, rather than the other, went home justified before God. For everyone who exalts himself will be humbled, and he who humbles himself will be exalted."
42Lk 18:15 People were also bringing babies to Jesus to have him touch them. When the disciples saw this, they rebuked them.
42Lk 18:16 But Jesus called the children to him and said, "Let the little children come to me, and do not hinder them, for the kingdom of God belongs to such as these.
42Lk 18:17 I tell you the truth, anyone who will not receive the kingdom of God like a little child will never enter it."
42Lk 18:18 A certain ruler asked him, "Good teacher, what must I do to inherit eternal life?"
42Lk 18:19 "Why do you call me good?" Jesus answered. "No one is good--except God alone.
42Lk 18:20 You know the commandments£º 'Do not commit adultery, do not murder, do not steal, do not give false testimony, honor your father and mother.'"
42Lk 18:21 "All these I have kept since I was a boy," he said.
42Lk 18:22 When Jesus heard this, he said to him, "You still lack one thing. Sell everything you have and give to the poor, and you will have treasure in heaven. Then come, follow me."
42Lk 18:23 When he heard this, he became very sad, because he was a man of great wealth.
42Lk 18:24 Jesus looked at him and said, "How hard it is for the rich to enter the kingdom of God!
42Lk 18:25 Indeed, it is easier for a camel to go through the eye of a needle than for a rich man to enter the kingdom of God."
42Lk 18:26 Those who heard this asked, "Who then can be saved?"
42Lk 18:27 Jesus replied, "What is impossible with men is possible with God."
42Lk 18:28 Peter said to him, "We have left all we had to follow you!"
42Lk 18:29 "I tell you the truth," Jesus said to them, "no one who has left home or wife or brothers or parents or children for the sake of the kingdom of God
42Lk 18:30 will fail to receive many times as much in this age and, in the age to come, eternal life."
42Lk 18:31 Jesus took the Twelve aside and told them, "We are going up to Jerusalem, and everything that is written by the prophets about the Son of Man will be fulfilled.
42Lk 18:32 He will be handed over to the Gentiles. They will mock him, insult him, spit on him, flog him and kill him.
42Lk 18:33 On the third day he will rise again."
42Lk 18:34 The disciples did not understand any of this. Its meaning was hidden from them, and they did not know what he was talking about.
42Lk 18:35 As Jesus approached Jericho, a blind man was sitting by the roadside begging.
42Lk 18:36 When he heard the crowd going by, he asked what was happening.
42Lk 18:37 They told him, "Jesus of Nazareth is passing by."
42Lk 18:38 He called out, "Jesus, Son of David, have mercy on me!"
42Lk 18:39 Those who led the way rebuked him and told him to be quiet, but he shouted all the more, "Son of David, have mercy on me!"
42Lk 18:40 Jesus stopped and ordered the man to be brought to him. When he came near, Jesus asked him,
42Lk 18:41 "What do you want me to do for you?" "Lord, I want to see," he replied.
42Lk 18:42 Jesus said to him, "Receive your sight; your faith has healed you."
42Lk 18:43 Immediately he received his sight and followed Jesus, praising God. When all the people saw it, they also praised God.
42Lk 19:1 Jesus entered Jericho and was passing through.
42Lk 19:2 A man was there by the name of Zacchaeus; he was a chief tax collector and was wealthy.
42Lk 19:3 He wanted to see who Jesus was, but being a short man he could not, because of the crowd.
42Lk 19:4 So he ran ahead and climbed a sycamore-fig tree to see him, since Jesus was coming that way.
42Lk 19:5 When Jesus reached the spot, he looked up and said to him, "Zacchaeus, come down immediately. I must stay at your house today."
42Lk 19:6 So he came down at once and welcomed him gladly.
42Lk 19:7 All the people saw this and began to mutter, "He has gone to be the guest of a 'sinner.'"
42Lk 19:8 But Zacchaeus stood up and said to the Lord, "Look, Lord! Here and now I give half of my possessions to the poor, and if I have cheated anybody out of anything, I will pay back four times the amount."
42Lk 19:9 Jesus said to him, "Today salvation has come to this house, because this man, too, is a son of Abraham.
42Lk 19:10 For the Son of Man came to seek and to save what was lost."
42Lk 19:11 While they were listening to this, he went on to tell them a parable, because he was near Jerusalem and the people thought that the kingdom of God was going to appear at once.
42Lk 19:12 He said£º "A man of noble birth went to a distant country to have himself appointed king and then to return.
42Lk 19:13 So he called ten of his servants and gave them ten minas. 'Put this money to work,' he said, 'until I come back.'
42Lk 19:14 "But his subjects hated him and sent a delegation after him to say, 'We don't want this man to be our king.'
42Lk 19:15 "He was made king, however, and returned home. Then he sent for the servants to whom he had given the money, in order to find out what they had gained with it.
42Lk 19:16 "The first one came and said, 'Sir, your mina has earned ten more.'
42Lk 19:17 "'Well done, my good servant!' his master replied. 'Because you have been trustworthy in a very small matter, take charge of ten cities.'
